			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Please someone explain to me....<a name="67786"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 22 04 10:46 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>1) Enrage
<br />
-Basically, a critter just ripostes everything while enrage is on.  
<br />

<br />
The tank should be continuing to taunt (or whatever) and will turn off attack so as not to become dead when everything gets riposted. 
<br />

<br />
For a bard, either be behind the critter or turn off attack at 10% health or both.  It's easiest to just turn off attack and let the casters finish things off. 
<br />

<br />
2.) Flurry
<br />
-The critter does extra attacks on whoever has aggro.  
<br />

<br />
It's not really something a bard needs to worry about much.  It's more for healers to be aware that a critter can do something like this and step up the healing when it happens. 
<br />

<br />
3.)Rampage
<br />
-Once in a while, the critter will be hitting a secondary target, usually the second person on the hate list.  If that person dies, the critter will work it's way down the hate list, hitting the highest person that is in range. 
<br />

<br />
A solid tactic is to have the Rampage tank pull the critter, and have the main tank then take aggro and tank it.  A healer or two keeps the rampage tank up, while the bulk of the healers keep the MT up. 
<br />

<br />
There's also AE Rampage, which is where a critter hits everything on his hate list that's in melee range.  
<br />

<br />
4.)Why do you wall or corner a mob?
<br />
-Easy answer, movement. 
<br />

<br />
When a tank is getting hit and a critter is getting hit they each move.  It's very difficult to balance something in the middle of a room, in any long fight you end up dancing in kind of a wierd circle with all the melees continually scurrying around the thing trying to stay behind it and the tank moving and getting summoned.  
<br />

<br />
Having a tank backed into a corner keeps the tank stationary, and it keeps the critter relatively stationary too, and it's back to the melees.  </span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><a href ="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=456989">Idril Galelin</a></span></td>
